Inputs.name: Vertex Color
Inputs.description:
RGBA values that determine the way the leaves bend at a detailed level.
		These values are typically painted onto the vertices of the mesh by an
		artist working in a DCC tool like 3ds Max or Maya.

		-	The red channel determines the stiffness of the leaves' edges.
		-	The green channel determines per-leaf phase variation. By painting leaves
			with different intensities in this channel, you can avoid having all your
			leaves moving in the same direction at the same time.
		-	The blue channel determines overall stiffness of the leaves.
		-	The alpha channel is used for pre-computed ambient occlusion.

		Required.

		for metallic surfaces this becomes the specular RGB. Input value is an RGB color in

Inputs.name: Opacity
Inputs.description:
An optional opacity of the pixel being shaded. Values closer to `0` are more transparent;
		values closer to `1` are more opaque. Note that this value is used differently
		depending on the value of the *Blend Mode* option.

		Default value: `0.5`.

Inputs.name: Opacity Threshold
Inputs.description:
When the *Blend Mode* option is set to *Opaque (G-buffer)*, and a value is set for the
		*Opacity* input, this value sets the threshold at which the surface becomes
		visible. When the opacity input value is below this threshold, the mesh is not
		shaded (fully transparent). When the opacity input value is above this
		threshold, the mesh is fully opaque.

		Default value: `0.5`.

Inputs.name: Normal
Inputs.description:
A directional vector perpendicular to the surface being shaded. Use this input
		to apply a normal map that contains small-scale details in the relief of the
		surface. Note that this vector should either be in tangent space or world space depending
		on the value of *Normals In*

Inputs.name: Metallic
Inputs.description:
Setting this to `1.0` makes the pixel reflect light as a conductor, or metallic surface.
		Setting this to `0.0` makes the pixel reflect light as a dielectric, like plastic.
		Anything in between blends between a dielectric and conductor. Note: This value affects how
		`Base Color` is interpreted.

		Default value: `0`

Inputs.name: Roughness
Inputs.description:
The amount of roughness on the surface. Values closer to `0` produce
		a more glossy finish; values closer to `1` produce a more matte finish.

		Default value: `0.5`

Inputs.name: Emissive
Inputs.description:
An optional RGB color of light that the surface being shaded should emit into
		the scene. Input value is an RGB color in linear color space.

Inputs.name: Ambient Occlusion
Inputs.description:
A scalar value that applies a faint shadowing effect, typically based on the
		presence of other nearby objects. Values closer to `0` produce stronger
		shadowing; values closer to `1` produce less shadowing.

		Default value: `1`

Inputs.name: Density
Inputs.description:
For surfaces with *Matarial Type* set to *Translucent*, this value determines how
		much the surface scatters incoming light. Values closer to `0` produce more scatter
		and let through more light; values closer to `1` minimizes the light scatter.

		Default value: `1`

Inputs.name: Light Color
Inputs.description:
The color of the light that the dynamic light source using this material
		should emit.

Inputs.name: Mask Threshold

Inputs.description:
The blend weight between the original input color and its fully grayscale equivalent.
		A value of `0` leaves the input color unaltered. A value of `1` (or higher)
		produces a fully grayscale final result.

		Default value: `1`.

Inputs.name: Luminance
Inputs.description:
Determines the brightness of each channel in the desaturated color. This allows you
		to compensate for the way the human eye perceives the relative lightness of different
		colors.

		This value is expressed as a coefficient for each color channel. To determine the
		grayscale color, the value of each color channel is multiplied by the coefficient
		for that channel, and the three channel values are added.

		For example, setting a value of `(1, 0, 0)` makes red areas in the original image
		come through as white, while blue and green areas come through as black.

		Some common luminance settings are:

		-	`(0.3, 0.6, 0.1)` (the default value if this slot is not connected)
		-	`(0.2126, 0.7152, 0.0722)` (the [BT 709](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rec._709) standard)
		-	`(0.299, 0.587, 0.114)` (the [BT 601](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rec._601) standard)

		about half of the parallax scale value, so that the median of the low and high
		points will lie approximately on the level of the original mesh surface.

		Default value: `0.02`

		to input *B*.

Inputs.name: Mip Level

		omitted, this value is determined internally based on the apparent size
		of the mesh being shaded.

A linear RGBA value that represents the color value stored in the
		skydome at the specified UV coordinates.

Inputs.description: The second normal map to blend in.

Inputs.description: The angle or set of angles that will be operated on.

Inputs.name: Position offset
Inputs.description:
An optional world-space offset to apply to the position of the pixel being
		shaded, changing the apparent placement of the object in the scene.

Inputs.name: Last Position offset
Inputs.description:
An optional last frame world-space offset to supply if a user is using the
		Position Offset option to be able to calculate velocities to accuratly do
		temporal based effects without artifacts.

Inputs.name: Base Color
Inputs.description: The RGB color of the pixel being shaded.

Inputs.name: Opacity
Inputs.description:
The opacity of the pixel being shaded. Values closer to `0` are more transparent;
		values closer to `1` are more opaque. Note that this value is used differently
		depending on the value of the *Blend Mode* option.

		Default value: `0.5`.

Inputs.name: Opacity Threshold
Inputs.description:
When the *Blend Mode* option is set to *Opaque*, and a value is set for the
		*Opacity* input, this value sets the threshold at which the mesh becomes
		visible. When the opacity input value is below this threshold, the mesh is not
		shaded (fully transparent). When the opacity input value is above this
		threshold, the mesh is fully opaque.

		Regardless of the *Blend Mode* setting, whenever there is both an emissive color
		and an opacity value set, this value sets the opacity threshold at which the
		emissive effect becomes visible.

		Default value: `0.5`.

Inputs.name: Normal
Inputs.description:
A directional vector perpendicular to the surface being shaded. Use this input
		to apply a normal map that contains small-scale details in the relief of the
		surface.

Inputs.name: Metallic
Inputs.description:
The "shininess" and reflectivity of the surface. Values closer to `0`
		produce a duller surface; values closer to `1` produce a shinier and
		more reflective surface.

		Default value: `0`

Inputs.name: Roughness
Inputs.description:
The amount of fine roughness on the surface. Values closer to `0` produce
		a more glossy finish; values closer to `1` produce a more matte finish.

		Default value: `0.5`

Inputs.name: Tessellation Factor
Inputs.description:
Optional parameter to control the tessellation factor used when the hardware
		tessellation option in the node properties is enabled. A lower value will result
		in a less tessellated mesh. Make sure that you also set the `Hardware Tesselation`
		option in the node properties.

		Note: For the constant tessellation option, this value drives the constant
		tessellation of the surface. To implement adaptive tessellation, you can
		make your graph compute the input value based on the distance to the camera
		(the length of the eye vector).

		If you intend to get your tesselation factor input values from a texture,
		use the **Sampling > Domain Sample Texture** node to sample the texture.

		Default value: `0.001`
		Min value: `0.001`
		Max value: `16`

Inputs.name: World Displacement
Inputs.description:
The distance to displace the tesselated vertices in meters. This value can be
		either a scalar value for height-based displacement or a vector3 value for
		vector based displacement.

		If you intend to get your displacement input values from a texture,
		use the **Sampling > Domain Sample Texture** node to sample the texture.

Inputs.name: Emissive
Inputs.description:
An optional color of light that the surface being shaded should emit into
		the scene.

Inputs.name: Ambient Occlusion
Inputs.description:
A scalar value that applies a faint shadowing effect, typically based on the
		presence of other nearby objects. Values closer to `0` produce stronger
		shadowing; values closer to `1` produce less shadowing.

		Default value: `1`

Inputs.name: Refraction
Inputs.description:
For partially transparent surfaces, this value defines the refractivity of
		the material: how much it bends the light that passes through it. Values
		closer to `0` bend the light more strongly; values closer to `1` produces
		less deflection.

		Default value: `1`

Inputs.name: Density
Inputs.description:
For partially transparent surfaces, this value determines how much the mesh
		scatters incoming light. Values closer to `0` produce more scatter and more of
		a glowing effect; values closer to `1` minimize the scatter.

		Default value: `1`

Inputs.name: Clear Coat Roughness
Inputs.description:
When the material type is "Clear Coat" this input allows you to control the
		roughness of the top clear coat layer

		Default value: `0`

Inputs.name: A
Inputs.description: The number or set of numbers that will be operated on.

Outputs.name: Out
Outputs.description: The decimal fraction of each channel in the input value.
